<TITLE>Bayesian Adaptive Research Design, Prof. Kruschke</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="khaki">

<center>
<h2> P747 Bayesian Adaptive Research Design.  <br> Spring 2011,
Section 16650, Fridays 9:05am-11:50am, Room 230 of Psychology Bldg.
</h2> <br>UNDER CONSTRUCTION!  </center>

<p><b>Motivation:</b>

<br>The FDA says so: <a
href="http://www.fda.gov/MedicalDevices/DeviceRegulationandGuidance/GuidanceDocuments/ucm071072.htm"
target="_blank">Guidance for the use of Bayesian statistics in medical
device clinical trials</a>. See Section 2.6, regarding benefits of
using Bayesian methods.


<p><b>Required textbook:</b> 
<br>&bull; Berry, S. M., Carlin, B. P., Lee, J. J., &amp; Muller, P. (2011).
<i>Bayesian Adaptive Methods for Clinical Trials</i>.  Boca Raton: CRC
Press.  ISBN: 9781439825488. <br>The book has a web site with programs
for examples in the book.

<p><b>Other required readings</b> are being planned and will be
announced. Candidate readings include the following:

<br>&bull; Cavagnaro, D. R., Myung, J. I., Pitt, M. A., &amp; Kujala,
J. V. (2010). Adaptive design optimization: A mutual information-based
approach to model discrimination in cognitive science. <i>Neural
Computation</i>, <b>22</b>, 887-905.

<br>&bull; Loredo, T. J., &amp; Chernoff, D. F. (2003). Bayesian adaptive
exploration. In: E. D. Feigelson &amp; G. J. Babu (Eds.),
<i>Statistical Challenges in Astronomy</i>, Ch. 4, pp. 57-70. New
York: Springer.

<br>&bull; something about adaptive testing, e.g. VanDerLindenP2010

<br>&bull; "Chapter 13: Goals, Power, and Sample Size" from <a
href="http://www.indiana.edu/~kruschke/DoingBayesianDataAnalysis/"
target="_blank">Kruschke, J. K. (2010). <i>Doing Bayesian data
analysis: A tutorial with R and BUGS</i>.</a>

<p><b>Pre-requisites:</b> <br>A previous course in Bayesian data
analysis, including experience with R and BUGS, such as <a
href="http://www.indiana.edu/~jkkteach/P533/"
target="_blank">P533</a>. We will be using R and BUGS to carry out the
examples presented in the required textbook (see the textbook web
site).


<p><b>Course format:</b> <br><i>This is a seminar-style course, not a
lecture-style course. Students will lead presentations of material.</i>

<p><b>Course grading:</b> Grades will be based on presentation quality
and participation when not presenting.

